How to measure the quality of the prediction¶

MSE¶

Most commonly used for regression is mean squared error $\text{MSE} = \cfrac{1}{N} \cdot \sum_i^N(y_i – \hat{y}_i)^2$

Pro: magnify and punish larger errors (where prediction is waaaayyy off from actual). Use when large errors are particularly undesirable. And MSE is differentiable (which is a very good property when the error is used for backpropagation in neural networks).

Contra: when data has outliers, MSE makes model more undesirable than it really is.

RMSE¶

For reporting, because the unit of measurement of MSE is squared, we typically take the root, and report the root mean squared error (RMSE) instead:

$\text{RMSE} = \sqrt(\text{MSE})$

In [15]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
mseError = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions, squared=True)
rmseError = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions, squared=False)
print('MSE is {:.2f}, RMSE is {:.2f}'.format(mseError, rmseError))

MSE is 3111.99, RMSE is 55.79

MAE¶

Mean absolute error $\text{MAE} =\cfrac{1}{N} \cdot \sum_i^N \left|(y_i – \hat{y}_i) \right|$

Pro: it is linear to the difference between prediction and actual, therefore more intuitive. It is more robust to outliers.

Contra: it is not differentiable.

MAPE¶

If it is more important to know the MAE proportional to the mean, we can use mean absolute percentage error $\text{MAPE} = \cfrac{1}{N} \cdot \sum_i^N \left|\cfrac{y_i – \hat{y}_i}{y_i} \right|$

Pro: it shows relative error to the mean.

Contra: it breaks when some actual values are zero. It is also biased when the actual value is very small. A more detailed comparison is here: https://www.statworx.com/at/blog/what-the-mape-is-falsely-blamed-for-its-true-weaknesses-and-better-alternatives/

Both MSE/RMSE and MAE/MAPE are lower the better.

A very good comparsion is here: https://medium.com/human-in-a-machine-world/mae-and-rmse-which-metric-is-better-e60ac3bde13d

In [18]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_absolute_percentage_error
maeError = mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions)
mapeError = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, predictions)
print('MAE is {:.2f}, MAPE is {:.2f}'.format(maeError, mapeError))

MAE is 43.78, MAPE is 0.34

The coefficient of determination or R-squared: $R^2 = 1-\cfrac{\sum_i^N(y_i – \hat{y}_i)^2}{\sum_i^N(y_i – \bar{y}_i)^2}$, represents the proportion of explanable variance of the dependent variables (how much variance is explained by the linear regression model). It is bigger the better, meaning the regression model has taken into account a larger part of the variance.

Pro: it is proportional, therefore not affected by scaling. It is always between 0 and 1. Recommend to use when the data has a small mean but large skewness.

Contra: it is hard to explain to people. And it cannot be used for nonlinear regression. A good explanation here: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/359906/is-r-squared-truly-an-invalid-metric-for-non-linear-models

Adjusted R-squared: adjusted for small number of samples compared to the number of independent variables (a "fat" dataset). It can be used to determine if a feature is necessary. The value of Adjusted R-squared decreases if the increase in the R square by the additional variable isn’t significant enough.

https://towardsdatascience.com/forecast-kpi-rmse-mae-mape-bias-cdc5703d242d

A comprehensive list of metrics in sklearn is here:

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/classes.html#regression-metrics

A little extra: about cross-validation¶

Overfitting: when sample data size is small and features are too many, the model may learn to perfectly fit the existing data and totally fail on new data.

There are ways to prevent overfitting, e.g., cross-validation, prunning in decision trees, dropout in neural networks, etc.

What we just did, to split into training and test set, is the hold-out method in cross validation.

Another common cross-validation method is K-fold. We divide the training set into portions, train on e.g., 9/10 th of the data and validate on the remaining 1 portion, and train again with different remaining portions. the model performance will be the average of the ten runs.

For classification problems, if the data has minority classes, we need to make sure that the minority classes are present in the training set. This is called the stratified K-fold. But since we are doing regression, we omit this part.

A good overview here: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/05/4-ways-to-evaluate-your-machine-learning-model-cross-validation-techniques-with-python-code/

At the end of this post, there is a very good discussion on bias-variance tradeoff of the cross-validation methods, it is extra of the extra, but definitely worth a closer look.

In sklearn, cross_val_score offers calculation of different metrics. Because sklearn in general maximizes scores, so in the cases of merics that need to be minimized, they add a negative sign in front of it. The actual score is just the positive version. Details here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html

In [33]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10)
cv_results = cross_val_score(linearRegr, x_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
print('linear regression cross-validation mse: {:.2f}'.format(-cv_results.mean()))

linear regression cross-validation mse: 3034.82

Some other regression algorithms¶

Ridge and Lasso reggression: r1 and r2 regulation: another way of preventing overfitting by penalizing large coefficients. Ridge adds the square of coefficients in cost function for minimization (r2 regularization), whereas Lasso adds the coefficients themselves (r1 regularization).

Difference in pratical use: Lasso can select features, making some coefficients zero. A very good explanation here:

https://towardsdatascience.com/ridge-and-lasso-regression-a-complete-guide-with-python-scikit-learn-e20e34bcbf0b

Another explanation from the perspective of bias vs. variance: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/lasso-vs-ridge-vs-elastic-net-ml/

Rule-of-thumb: when you have features with small/medium sized effects, go with Ridge. If you have a lot of variables but only a few with a medium/large effect, go with Lasso. But when you only have a few variables anyway, you may want to use Ridge to keep them all in your models.

In [35]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, Lasso
ridgeRegr = Ridge()
ridgeRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)
predictions_ridge = ridgeRegr.predict(x_test)
rmseError_ridge = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_ridge, squared=False)

lassoRegr = Lasso()
lassoRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)
predictions_lasso = lassoRegr.predict(x_test)
rmseError_lasso = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_lasso, squared=False)
print('Ridge RMSE is {:.2f}, Lasso RMSE is {:.2f}'.format(rmseError_ridge, rmseError_lasso))

Ridge RMSE is 57.77, Lasso RMSE is 61.02

Random forest for regression: through sample randomization and feature randomization, random forest is less prone to overfitting. More references here: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/36298/why-is-pruning-not-needed-for-random-forest-trees

For the same reasons, random forest usually does not require cross-validation to prevent overfitting. A related discussion here: https://datascience.stackexchange.com/questions/6510/does-modeling-with-random-forests-require-cross-validation

However, it does have generalization problems and problem with sparse data input, compared to e.g. linear regression models: https://medium.com/swlh/random-forest-fails-a8ca2d46c312

Parameters here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.html

In [26]:

predictions = rfRegr.predict(x_test)
